# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abraham-lincoln
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 30 to December 2, 1840.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the shadow of an incomplete economic recovery from the Panic of 1837, Whig nominee William Henry Harrison defeated incumbent President Martin Van Buren of the Democratic Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The election marked the first of two Whig victories in presidential elections, but was the only one where they won a majority of the popular vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the third rematch in American history.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In 1839, the Whigs held a national convention for the first time.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1839 Whig National Convention saw 1836 nominee William Henry Harrison defeat former Secretary of State Henry Clay and General Winfield Scott.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren faced little opposition at the 1840 Democratic National Convention, but controversial Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson was not renominated.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats thus became the only major party since 1800 to fail to select a vice presidential nominee.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Referencing vice presidential nominee John Tyler and Harrison's participation in the Battle of Tippecanoe, the Whigs campaigned on the slogan of "Tippecanoe and Tyler Too." With Van Buren weakened by economic woes, Harrison won a popular majority and 234 of 294 electoral votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Voter participation surged as white male suffrage became nearly universal, and a contemporary record of 42.4% of the voting age population voted for Harrison.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren's loss made him the third president to lose re-election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs did not enjoy the benefits of victory.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 67-year-old Harrison, the oldest U.S. president elected until Ronald Reagan won the 1980 election, died a little more than a month after inauguration.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was succeeded by John Tyler, who unexpectedly proved not to be a Whig.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] While Tyler had been a staunch supporter of Clay at the convention, he was a former Democrat, a passionate supporter of states' rights, and effectively an independent.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] As President, Tyler blocked the Whigs' legislative agenda and was expelled from the Whig Party, subsequently the second independent (after Washington) to serve as president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren would be the last incumbent president to lose his reelection bid in a general election until fellow Democrat Grover Cleveland in 1888.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time a challenger to an incumbent president got a majority of the vote until 1932.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the last time as of 2024 where the incumbent president seeking re-election flipped a state yet failed to secure re-election, with Van Buren winning South Carolina, despite losing it four years earlier, and losing re-election to Harrison.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The first national convention of the Whig Party was called for by members of the party in Congress and it was attended by almost 250 delegates in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, William Henry Harrison, and Winfield Scott ran for the party's presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegations of each state balloted separately before meeting together with the other representatives of the states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Clay initially led on the first ballot, but Harrison won on the final ballot with 148 votes compared to Clay's 90 votes and Scott's 16 votes after supporters from Scott switched to Harrison.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] John Tyler was selected as a factional and geographical balance to Harrison.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic members of the New Hampshire General Court made a call for the 1840 Democratic National Convention which was held in Baltimore, Maryland in May 1840.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Delegates from twenty-two states attended the convention, but the sizes of the delegations varied with New Jersey having fifty-nine delegates to cast its eight votes while Massachusetts only had one delegate to cast its fourteen votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] A committee was formed to make recommendations for the nominations and the committee supported Van Buren for renomination which was approved by acclamation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, the vice-presidential nomination was left vacant due to opposition to Vice President Richard Mentor Johnson's personal life.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After the negative views of Freemasonry among a large segment of the public began to wane in the mid-1830s, the Anti-Masonic Party disintegrated.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Many leaders began to move to the Whig party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Remaining leaders met in September 1837 in Washington, and agreed to maintain the party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The third Anti-Masonic Party National Convention was held in Philadelphia on November 13–14, 1838.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] By this time, the party had been almost entirely supplanted by the Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates unanimously voted to nominate William Henry Harrison for president (who the party had supported for president the previous election along with Francis Granger for vice president) and Daniel Webster for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, when the Whig National Convention nominated Harrison with John Tyler as his running mate, the Anti-Masonic Party did not make an alternate nomination and ceased to function and was fully absorbed into the Whigs by 1840.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, Myron Holley, Joshua Leavitt, and Gerrit Smith proposed the creation of an anti-slavery party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In July 1839, two resolutions proposed by Holley at the American Anti-Slavery Society's meeting in Cleveland, called for the creation of an abolitionist party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nevertheless, the supporters nominated Birney and Francis Julius LeMoyne as a presidential ticket at a meeting in Warsaw, New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] However, Birney declined the presidential nomination as he preferred a nomination to be made by a regular body of abolitionists and LeMoyne also declined the vice-presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Smith and Holley made a call for an abolitionist nominating convention to be held on April 1, 1840, in Albany, New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 121 delegates attended the delegation and selected a presidential ticket of Birney and Thomas Earle. which was accepted.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Birney was unable to campaign during the election as he was in England until November.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party received opposition from followers of William Lloyd Garrison and abolitionist Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the wake of the Panic of 1837, Van Buren was widely unpopular, and Harrison, following Andrew Jackson's strategy, ran as a war hero and man of the people while presenting Van Buren as a wealthy snob living in luxury at the public expense.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Although Harrison was comfortably wealthy and well educated, his "log cabin" image caught fire, sweeping all sections of the country.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison avoided campaigning on the issues, with his Whig Party attracting a broad coalition with few common ideals.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig strategy overall was to win the election by avoiding discussion of difficult national issues such as slavery or the national bank and concentrate instead on exploiting dissatisfaction over the failed policies of the Van Buren administration with colorful campaigning techniques.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison was the first president to campaign actively for office.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] He did so with the slogan "Tippecanoe and Tyler too".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Tippecanoe referred to Harrison's military victory over a group of Shawnee Native Americans at a river in Indiana called Tippecanoe in 1811.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] For their part, Democrats laughed at Harrison for being too old for the presidency, and referred to him as "Granny", hinting that he was senile.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs took advantage of this quip and declared that Harrison was "the log cabin and hard cider candidate", a man of the common people from the rough-and-tumble West.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] They depicted Harrison's opponent, President Martin Van Buren, as a wealthy snob who was out of touch with the people.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, it was Harrison who came from a family of wealthy planters, while Van Buren's father was a tavernkeeper.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison however moved to the frontier and for years lived in a log cabin, while Van Buren had been a well-paid government official.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, the election was held in the wake of the Panic of 1837, one of the worst economic depressions in the nation's history, and voters blamed Van Buren, seeing him as unsympathetic to struggling citizens.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] 31.9% of the voting age population and 80.3% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time that a majority of southern voters participated in the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison won the support of western settlers and eastern bankers alike.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 1,179 counties/independent cities making returns, Harrison won in 699 (59.29%) while Van Buren carried 477 (40.46%).
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Three counties (0.25%) in the South split evenly between Harrison and Van Buren.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The extent of Van Buren's unpopularity was evident in Harrison's victories in New York, the president's home state, and in Tennessee, where Andrew Jackson himself had come out of retirement to stump for his former vice-president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time a Democratic president lost re-election, as well as the first of only two times (the other being 1980) that a Democratic president lost re-election and lost the popular vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was also the first election in U.S. history in which a candidate won more than a million popular votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election where Indiana voted for the Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only election where the Whigs won Maine, Michigan, and Mississippi.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in American history in which a majority of voters in Alabama and a majority of voters in Mississippi voted for different candidates.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] The 1840 presidential election was the only time in which four people who either had been or would become a U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] President (Van Buren, Harrison, Tyler, and Polk) received at least one vote in the Electoral College when it voted for president and vice-president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Harrison's victory won him precious little time as chief executive of the United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] After giving the longest inauguration speech in U.S. history (lasting about 1 hour and 45 minutes, in cold weather and rain), Harrison served only one month as president before dying of pneumonia on April 4, 1841.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] Source: Data from Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–257.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] In the 1997 film *Amistad*, Van Buren (played by Nigel Hawthorne) is seen campaigning for re-election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1840-united-states-presidential-election] These scenes have been criticized for their historical inaccuracy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk narrowly defeated Whig nominee Henry Clay in a close contest turning on the controversial issues of slavery and the annexation of the Republic of Texas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This is the only election in which both major party nominees served as Speaker of the House at one point, and the first in which neither candidate held elective office at the time.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] President John Tyler's pursuit of Texas annexation divided both major parties.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Annexation would geographically expand American slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It also risked war with Mexico while the United States engaged in sensitive possession and boundary negotiations with Great Britain, which controlled Canada, over Oregon.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Texas annexation thus posed both domestic and foreign policy risks.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties had wings in the North and the South, but the possibility of the expansion of slavery threatened a sectional split in each party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Expelled by the Whig Party after vetoing key Whig legislation and lacking a firm political base, Tyler hoped to use the annexation of Texas to win the presidency as an independent or at least to have decisive, pro-Texas influence over the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The initial frontrunner for the Democratic nomination was former President Martin Van Buren, but his opposition to the annexation of Texas damaged his candidacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition from former President Andrew Jackson and most Southern delegations, plus a nomination rule change specifically aimed to block him, prevented Van Buren from winning the necessary two-thirds vote of delegates to the 1844 Democratic National Convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk, former Governor of Tennessee and Speaker.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He was the first successful dark horse for the presidency.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk ran on a platform embracing popular commitment to expansion, often referred to as Manifest Destiny.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler dropped out of the race and endorsed Polk.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs nominated Henry Clay, a famous, long-time party leader who was the early favorite but who conspicuously waffled on Texas annexation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Though a Southerner from Kentucky and a slave owner, Clay chose to focus on the risks of annexation while claiming not to oppose it personally.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His awkward, repeated attempts to adjust and finesse his position on Texas confused and alienated voters, contrasting negatively with Polk's consistent clarity.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk successfully linked the dispute with Britain over Oregon with the Texas issue.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic nominee thus united anti-slavery Northern expansionists, who demanded Oregon, with pro-slavery Southern expansionists who demanded Texas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the national popular vote, Polk beat Clay by fewer than 40,000 votes, a margin of 1.4%.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney of the anti-slavery Liberty Party won 2.3% of the vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Electoral College winner was decided by New York where Polk won by just over 5,100 votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Had Clay won the state, he would have won the presidency with 141 electoral votes to Polk's 134.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney's vote share in New York exceeded Polk's margin of victory over Clay, marking the first time a third party candidate vote share exceeded the margin of a winning candidate in a decisive state. of a United States presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After Polk's victory, Tyler annexed Texas, which was the proximate cause of the Mexican–American War during Polk's presidency.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs and Democrats embarked upon their campaigns during the climax of the congressional gag rule controversies in 1844, which prompted Southern congressmen to suppress northern petitions to end the slave trade in the District of Columbia.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-annexation petitions to Congress sent from northern anti-slavery forces, including state legislatures, were similarly suppressed.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Intra-party sectional compromises and maneuvering on slavery politics during these divisive debates placed significant strain on the northern and southern wings that comprised each political organization.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The question as to whether the institution of slavery and its aristocratic principles of social authority were compatible with democratic republicanism was becoming "a permanent issue in national politics".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In 1836, a portion of the Mexican state of Coahuila y Tejas declared its independence to form the Republic of Texas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Texans, mostly American immigrants from the Deep South, many of whom owned slaves, sought to bring their republic into the Union as a state.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] At first, the subject of annexing Texas to the United States was shunned by both major American political parties.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Although they recognized Texas sovereignty, Presidents Andrew Jackson (1829–1837) and Martin Van Buren (1837–1841) declined to pursue annexation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The prospect of bringing another slave state into the Union was fraught with problems.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Both major parties – the Democrats and Whigs – viewed Texas statehood as something "not worth a foreign war [with Mexico]" or the "sectional combat" that annexation would provoke in the United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The incumbent President John Tyler, formerly vice-president, had assumed the presidency upon the death of William Henry Harrison in 1841.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler, a Whig in name only, emerged as a states' rights advocate committed to slavery expansion in defiance of Whig principles.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After he vetoed the Whig domestic legislative agenda, he was expelled from his own party on September 13, 1841.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Politically isolated, but unencumbered by party restraints, Tyler aligned himself with a small faction of Texas annexationists in a bid for election to a full term in 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler became convinced that Great Britain was encouraging a Texas–Mexico rapprochement that might lead to slave emancipation in the Texas republic.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Accordingly, he directed Secretary of State Abel P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Upshur of Virginia to initiate, then relentlessly pursue, secret annexation talks with Texas minister to the United States Isaac Van Zandt, beginning on October 16, 1843.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler submitted his Texas-U.S. treaty for annexation to the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Senate, delivered April 22, 1844, where a two-thirds majority was required for ratification.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The newly appointed Secretary of State John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun of South Carolina (assuming his post March 29, 1844) included a document known as the Packenham Letter with the Tyler bill that was calculated to inject a sense of crisis in Southern Democrats of the Deep South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In it, he characterized slavery as a social blessing and the acquisition of Texas as an emergency measure necessary to safeguard the "peculiar institution" in the United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Tyler and Calhoun sought to unite the South in a crusade that would present the North with an ultimatum: support Texas annexation or lose the South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Whigs considered Texas annexation particularly egregious, since Mexico had outlawed slavery in Coahuila y Tejas in 1829, before Texas independence had been declared.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 1844 presidential campaigns evolved within the context of this struggle over Texas annexation, which was tied to the question of slavery expansion and national security.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] All candidates in the 1844 presidential election had to declare a position on this explosive issue.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Martin Van Buren, President of the United States between 1837 and 1841, and chief architect of Jacksonian democracy, was the presumptive Democratic presidential contender in the spring of 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun withdrawing his bid for the presidency in January 1844, the campaign was expected to focus on domestic issues.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren regarded the Tyler annexation measure as an attempt to sabotage his bid for the White House by exacerbating the already strained North-South Democratic alliance regarding slavery expansion.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation of Texas was the chief political issue of the day.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, initially the leading candidate, opposed immediate annexation because it might lead to a sectional crisis over the status of slavery in the West and lead to war with Mexico.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This position cost Van Buren the support of southern and expansionist Democrats; as a result, he failed to win the nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates likewise could not settle on Lewis Cass, the former Secretary of War, whose credentials also included past service as a U.S. minister to France.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On the eighth ballot, the historian George Bancroft, a delegate from Massachusetts, proposed former House Speaker James K.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk argued that Texas and Oregon had always belonged to the United States by right.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He called for "the immediate re-annexation of Texas" and for the "re-occupation" of the disputed Oregon territory.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On the next roll call, the convention unanimously accepted Polk, who became the first dark horse, or little-known, presidential candidate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates selected Senator Silas Wright of New York for Vice President, but Wright, an admirer of Van Buren, declined the nomination to become the second person to decline a vice presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren realized that accommodating slavery expansionists in the South would open the Northern Democrats to charges of appeasement to the Slave power from the strongly anti-annexation Northern Whigs and some Democrats.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He crafted an emphatically anti-Texas position that temporized with expansionist southern Democrats, laying out a highly conditional scenario that delayed Texas annexation indefinitely.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the Hammett letter, published April 27, 1844 (penned April 20), he counseled his party to reject Texas under a Tyler administration.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Furthermore, annexation of Texas as a territory would proceed, tentatively, under a Van Buren administration, only when the American public had been consulted on the matter and Mexico's cooperation had been pursued to avoid an unnecessary war.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A military option might be advanced if a groundswell of popular support arose for Texas, certified with a congressional mandate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In these respects, Martin Van Buren differed from Henry Clay, who would never tolerate annexation without Mexico's assent.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] With the publication of Clay's Raleigh Letter and Van Buren's Hammett letter, Van Burenite Democrats hoped that their candidate's posture on Texas would leave southern pro-annexationists with exactly one choice for president: Martin Van Buren.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In this, they misjudged the political situation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler and the southern pro-annexationists posed a potentially far greater threat than Clay, in that the Tyler-Calhoun treaty would put immense pressure on the northern Democrats to comply with southern Democrats' demands for Texas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Hammett letter utterly failed to reassure Middle and Deep South extremists who had responded favorably to Calhoun's Pakenham Letter.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A minority of the southern Democrat leadership remained obdurate that Northern Democratic legislators would ignore their constituents' opposition to slavery expansion and unite in support of Texas annexation once exposed to sufficient southern pressure.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Former President Andrew Jackson publicly announced his support for immediate Texas annexation in May 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Jackson had facilitated Tyler's Texas negotiations in February 1844 by reassuring Sam Houston, the President of Texas, that the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As the Senate debated the Tyler treaty, Jackson declared that the popular support among Texans for annexation should be respected, and any delay would result in a British dominated Texas Republic that would promote slave emancipation and pose a foreign military threat to the southwest United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The former military hero went further, urging all Jacksonian Democrats to block Martin Van Buren from the party ticket and seek a Democratic presidential candidate fully committed to the immediate annexation of Texas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In doing so, Jackson abandoned the traditional Jeffersonian-Jacksonian formula that had required its Northern and Southern wings to compromise on constitutional slavery disputes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Texas issue was fracturing Van Buren's support among Democrats and would derail his candidacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk furthermore pledged to serve only one term as president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He would keep this promise, and would die less than three months after leaving office.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation treaty needed a two-thirds vote and was easily defeated in the Senate, largely along partisan lines, 16 to 35 – a two-thirds majority against passage – on June 8, 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs voted 27–1 against the treaty: all northern Whig senators voted nay, and fourteen of fifteen southern Whig senators had joined them.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats voted for the treaty 15–8, with a slight majority of Northern Democrats opposing.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Democrats affirmed the treaty 10–1, with only one slave state senator, Thomas Hart Benton, voting against.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Three days later, Tyler and his supporters in Congress began exploring means to bypass the supermajority requirement for Senate treaty approval.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Substituting the constitutional protocols for admitting regions of the United States into the Union as states, Tyler proposed that alternative, yet constitutional, means be used to bring the Republic of Texas – a foreign country – into the Union.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler and Calhoun, formerly staunch supporters of minority safeguards based on the supermajority requirements for national legislation, now altered their position to facilitate passage of the Tyler treaty.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler's attempt to evade the Senate vote launched a spirited congressional debate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay of Kentucky, effectively the leader of the Whig Party since its inception in 1834, was selected as its nominee at the party's convention in Baltimore, Maryland, on May 1, 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay, a slaveholder, presided over a party in which its Southern wing was sufficiently committed to the national platform to put partisan loyalties above slavery expansionist proposals that might undermine its north–south alliance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs felt confident that Clay could duplicate Harrison's landslide victory of 1840 against any opposition candidate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Southern Whigs feared that the acquisition of the fertile lands in Texas would produce a huge market for slave labor, inflating the price of slaves and deflating land values in their home states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Whigs feared that Texas statehood would initiate the opening of a vast "Empire for Slavery".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Two weeks before the Whig convention in Baltimore, in reaction to Calhoun's Packenham Letter, Clay issued a document known as the Raleigh Letter (issued April 17, 1844) that presented his views on Texas to his fellow southern Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In it, he flatly denounced the Tyler annexation bill and predicted that its passage would provoke a war with Mexico, whose government had never recognized Texas independence.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay underlined his position, warning that even with Mexico's consent, he would block annexation in the event that substantial sectional opposition existed anywhere in the United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig party leadership was acutely aware that any proslavery legislation advanced by its southern wing would alienate its anti-slavery northern wing and cripple the party in the general election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In order to preserve their party, Whigs would need to stand squarely against acquiring a new slave state.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As such, Whigs were content to restrict their 1844 campaign platform to less divisive issues such as internal improvements and national finance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Whigs picked Theodore Frelinghuysen of New Jersey – "the Christian Statesman" – as Clay's running mate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] An advocate of the colonization of emancipated slaves, he was acceptable to southern Whigs as an opponent of the abolitionists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His pious reputation balanced Clay's image as a slave-holding, hard-drinking duelist.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On July 27, 1844, Clay released a position statement, the so-called "Alabama Letter." In it, he counseled his Whig constituency to regard Texas annexation and statehood as merely a short phase in the decline of slavery in the United States, rather than a long term advance for the Slave Power.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay qualified his stance on Texas annexation, declaring "no personal objection to the annexation" of the republic.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] He would move back to his original orientation in September 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Northern Whigs expressed outrage at any détente with the Slave Power and accused him of equivocating on Texas annexation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's central position, however, had not altered: no annexation without northern acquiescence.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's commitment brought Southern Whigs under extreme pressure in their home states and congressional districts, threatening to tarnish their credentials as supporters of slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] After the closed session Senate debates on the Tyler-Texas treaty were leaked to the public on April 27, 1844, President Tyler's only hope of success in influencing passage of his treaty was to intervene directly as a spoiler candidate in the 1844 election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His "Democratic-Republican Party", a recycling of the name of Jefferson's party, held its convention on May 27, 1844, in Baltimore, Maryland, a short distance from the unfolding Democratic Party convention that would select James K.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler was nominated the same day without challenge, accepting the honor on May 30, 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Tyler delegates did not designate a vice-presidential running mate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk was faced with the possibility that a Tyler ticket might shift votes away from the Democrats and provide Clay with the margin of victory in a close race.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler made clear in his nomination acceptance speech that his overriding concern was the ratification of his Texas annexation treaty.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, he hinted that he would drop out of the race once that end was assured, informing Polk, through Senator Robert J.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Walker of Mississippi, that his campaign efforts were simply a vehicle to mobilize support for Texas annexation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Tyler concentrated his resources in the states of New York, Pennsylvania and New Jersey, all highly contested states in the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Securing enough Democratic support, his withdrawal might prove indispensable to Polk.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk was receptive as long as Tyler could withdraw without raising suspicion of a secret bargain.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] To solidify Tyler's cooperation, Polk enlisted Andrew Jackson to reassure Tyler that Texas annexation would be consummated under a Polk administration.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] On August 20, 1844, Tyler dropped out of the presidential race, and Tylerites moved quickly to support the Democratic Party nominee.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party held its 1843 national convention on August 30 in Buffalo, New York, with 148 delegates from twelve states in attendance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Birney, the party's presidential nominee in the 1840 election, was renominated with 108 votes on the first ballot (Thomas Morris and William Jay received 2 and 1 votes respectively).
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Morris would go on to be nominated for vice-president with 83 votes compared to Gerrit Smith's 22 and Alvan Stewart's 1.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The party received 2.3% of the popular vote in the election, which was the highest it ever received.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Joseph Smith, the mayor of Nauvoo, Illinois, and founder of the Latter-day Saint movement, ran as an independent under the newly created Reform Party with Sidney Rigdon as his running mate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] His top aide Brigham Young campaigned for Smith saying, "He it is that God of Heaven designs to save this nation from destruction and preserve the Constitution." The campaign ended when he was attacked and killed by a mob while in the Carthage, Illinois, jail on June 27, 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] 30.6% of the voting age population and 79% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk's adoption of Manifest Destiny paid dividends at the polls.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] No longer identified with the Tyler-Calhoun "southern crusade for slavery", the western Democrats could embrace Texas annexation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats enjoyed a huge upsurge in voter turnout, up to 20% over the figures from 1840, especially in the Northwest and Mid-Atlantic regions.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats won Michigan, Illinois, and Indiana and nearly took Ohio, where the concept of Manifest Destiny was most admired.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] In the Deep South, Clay lost every state to Polk, a huge reversal from the 1840 race, but carried most of the Middle and Border South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay's "waffling" on Texas may have cost him the 41 electoral votes of New York and Michigan.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The former slaveholder, now abolitionist, James Birney of the Liberty Party, received 15,812 and 3,632 votes, respectively, based on his unwavering stand against Texas annexation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Celebratory shots rang out in Washington on November 7 as returns came in from western New York which clinched the state and the presidency for Polk.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk won by a mere 5,106 out of 470,062 cast in New York, and only 3,422 out of 52,096 votes in Michigan.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Had enough of these voting blocks cast their ballots for the anti-annexationist Clay in New York, he would have defeated Polk.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Still, Clay's opposition to annexation and western slavery expansion served him well among Northern Whigs and nearly secured him the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Clay was the third of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Thomas Jefferson, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Clay and Bryan are the only two candidates to lose the presidency three times.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This is the most recent presidential election where the election took place on different days in different states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It is the only presidential election in which both major party nominees were former Speakers of the House.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which Ohio voted for the Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the only presidential election in which the winner, Polk, lost both his birth state of North Carolina and his state of residence, Tennessee, (which he lost by only 123 votes) before Donald Trump's victory in the 2016 presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of four times that a victorious candidate lost their home state followed by 1916, 1968, and 2016.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Polk's election confirmed that Manifest Destiny had majority support in the electorate despite Whig opposition.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The annexation of Texas was formalized on March 1, 1845, days before Polk took office.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Mexico refused to accept the annexation and the Mexican–American War broke out in 1846.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Instead of demanding all of Oregon, Polk compromised.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Washington and London negotiated the Buchanan–Pakenham Treaty, which split up the Oregon Territory between the two countries.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] Upon the conclusion of the election, Whig publications were disheartened at Henry Clay's loss against Polk's alleged fraud.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Almanac, a yearly collection of political statistics and events of interest to the party, contained in 1845 a column alleging fraud in Louisiana.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] It noted that, in one Louisiana parish, Plaquemines, the vote tally exploded from a 240 to 40 vote victory for the Van Buren ticket in 1840 to a 1007 to 37 vote victory for the Polk ticket in 1844.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 970 vote margin was greater than Polk's margin statewide.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] The 1,007 votes received by Polk exceeded the total number of all white males in the parish in 1840, despite Louisiana having a property requirement to vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A steward, pilot, and passenger of the steamboat *Agnes* reportedly said that the ship ferried voters from New Orleans to Plaquemines parish where the steward was pushed by the Captain to vote for the Polk ticket three times, despite not being of voting age.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1844-united-states-presidential-election] A man named Charles Bruland was seen driven out of the voting booth wounded and bloody after attempting to cast a vote for the Clay ticket in Plaquemines Parish.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] National conventions of the **Free Soil and Liberty parties** met in 1847 and 1848 to nominate candidates for president and vice president in advance of the 1848 United States presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] These assemblies resulted in the creation of the national Free Soil Party, a union of political abolitionists with antislavery Conscience Whigs and Barnburner Democrats to oppose the westward extension of slavery into the U.S. territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Former President Martin Van Buren was nominated for president by the Free Soil National Convention that met at Buffalo, New York on August 9, 1848; Charles Francis Adams Sr. was nominated for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Van Buren and Adams received 291,409 popular votes in the national election, almost all from the free states; his popularity among northern Democrats was great enough to deny his Democratic rival, Lewis Cass, the crucial state of New York, throwing the state and the election to Whig Zachary Taylor.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The organizers of the Liberty Party found themselves at a crossroads following the 1844 United States elections.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The party had experienced rapid growth from 1840 to 1844, particularly in New England, where Liberty candidates were elected to state legislative offices.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In 1844, the Liberty nominees for president and vice president, James G.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Birney and Thomas Morris, received 62,025 votes in the 13 free states, representing 2.30% of the national total.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In New York and Michigan the Liberty vote was more than the margin separating Democrat James K.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] After 1844, the party's growth plateaued, and party leaders began to consider the future trajectory of the movement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Chase, one group favored cooperation with anti-slavery Whigs and Democrats, even suggesting Liberty candidates should be willing to withdraw in favor of major party candidates who pledged opposition to slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] This strategy was most successful in New Hampshire, where in 1846 a coalition of Liberty men, Whigs, and Independent Democrats elected John P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Others opposed any cooperation with the major parties and argued the Liberty Party should adopt a broad reform platform in order to appeal to voters outside the antislavery movement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] This group organized the Liberty League to promote their ideas within the party and included political abolitionists such as Gerrit Smith, William Goodell, and others.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Unlike in 1844, there was no obvious candidate who could command the unanimous support of the Liberty Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] While leaders of the Liberty League hoped to persuade Birney to stand for a third time, his reputation had been damaged by missteps during the 1844 campaign, and Birney himself was disinclined to run again.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The Liberty League met at Macedon Lock, New York over June 8–10, 1847 and nominated Smith for president and Elihu Burritt for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] (Burritt declined the nomination, and the League eventually promoted Charles C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Foote to be Smith's running mate.) Seventy delegates were in attendance, including Goodell, who presided over the meeting.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The convention adopted a platform endorsing an antislavery interpretation of the United States Constitution, free trade, abolition of the army and navy, and land reform.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Reflecting the influence of early feminists within the League, prominent female abolitionists Lydia Maria Child and Lucretia Mott received one vote apiece in the balloting for president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] A deputation from the Liberty League was present when the Liberty Party held their national convention at Buffalo, New York on October 20, 1847.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] They aimed to secure Smith's nomination by the national party on a platform accepting the resolves of the Macedon convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The faction led by Chase, meanwhile, continued to seek support from disaffected members of the two major parties.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In the months preceding the convention, they began to promote Hale as a candidate capable of uniting a broad coalition of Liberty men, Conscience Whigs, and Independent Democrats on the basis of opposition to slavery's extension.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] A contingent of Liberty leaders including Joshua Leavitt, Henry B.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Stanton, and John Greenleaf Whittier met with Hale in Boston in July 1847 to encourage him to make a public declaration of his candidacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Hale, however, was concerned that accepting the party's nomination would weaken his position in the Senate and asked for the convention to be delayed until the following spring.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] When the Chase faction failed to secure the delay of the convention, Hale wrote to Lewis Tappan requesting that his name not be placed in nomination at the Buffalo convention, but Tappan ignored this request.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Acceptance of Hale required a significant shift in the party's attitude and approach to politics.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Chase and his allies worked tirelessly throughout the summer in support of Hale's candidacy; their efforts were rewarded, as Hale was nominated overwhelmingly by the national convention, with 103 votes to 44 for Smith.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Former Ohio Supreme Court Justice Leicester King was nominated for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The nomination of Hale by the Liberty National Convention was a major victory for the coalitionists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Crucially, it secured a candidate who could be persuaded to withdraw if a coalition with antislavery Whigs and Democrats were later possible.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Events in the spring of 1848 soon presented such an opportunity.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The end of the Mexican-American War raised the question of westward expansion and the extension of slavery into the U.S. territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In 1846, northern Whigs crossed party lines to support a proposal by David Wilmot, a Democrat from Pennsylvania, to exclude slavery from all of the territory acquired from Mexico.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The 1848 Democratic National Convention repudiated the Wilmot Proviso and nominated Lewis Cass for president on a platform endorsing popular sovereignty.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Cass's nomination enraged supporters of former President Martin Van Buren, who had been denied the nomination of his party in 1844 due to his opposition to the annexation of Texas; they considered the rejection of Van Buren evidence of the party's subservience to the Slave Power.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The 1848 Whig National Convention at Philadelphia took no position on the Wilmot Proviso, but its candidate, General Zachary Taylor, was a slaveholder from Louisiana who had risen to prominence by his exploits in a war most abolitionists considered immoral.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Abolitionists thus faced a choice between a proslavery Democrat and a slaveholding Whig.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] These conditions were ripe for a third candidate to emerge and unite the support of antislavery men of all parties, as Chase and his allies had long anticipated.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In May 1848, Barnburners in New York, predicting a Cass victory, called for a convention of anti-Cass Democrats in Utica on June 22.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] This convention nominated Van Buren for president and Senator Henry Dodge for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In the aftermath of Taylor's nomination, a contingent of disgruntled Whigs led by Massachusetts delegates Henry Wilson and Charles Allen withdrew from the Philadelphia convention and called for a new meeting of antislavery advocates at Buffalo.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Both groups recognized the importance of uniting all antislavery voters under one roof; when Dodge declined the vice presidential nomination, it opened the door for the Barnburners to join the growing free soil movement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Members of the Liberty Party objected to Van Buren due to his opposition to the abolition of slavery in Washington, D.C. and his stance during the Amistad case.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Leavitt stated that they "cannot support him, without deliberately giving the lie to all our own declarations for fifteen years past" as Van Buren was a "Northern man with Southern principles".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The Buffalo Free Soil convention opened on August 9 with approximately 20,000 Democrats, Whigs, and Liberty men in attendance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Many of the Whigs hoped for the nomination of Supreme Court Justice John McLean, who had been available as a candidate for the Whig and Anti-Masonic parties in past elections.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Most Liberty men still supported Hale; but the importance of the Barnburners, by far the largest contingent of the new party, made Van Buren the early frontrunner for the nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] McLean soon found he lacked sufficient support to be nominated and withdrew his name from consideration; an informal vote within the committee of conferees found a majority in favor of Van Buren.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In exchange for Liberty support for Van Buren, Chase negotiated acceptance of much of the Liberty Party's platform, including the non-extension of slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] As a gesture to the party's Whig element, Charles Francis Adams Sr., son of the late John Quincy Adams, was nominated for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Like the Liberty platform of 1844, but unlike the more radical Liberty League document, the national platform of the Free Soil Party accepted the premise that the United States Congress had no legal or constitutional authority to abolish slavery in the slave states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Instead, it occupied the narrower ground of opposing the admission of new slave states and territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The platform made no mention of the Fugitive Slave Act of 1793 or the civil and political rights of African Americans, unlike previous Liberty Party documents.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] It included planks endorsing traditional Democratic economic policies which many in the Liberty Party had long supported, including a federal homestead act, as well as public support for internal improvements.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The acolytes of the Liberty League were unimpressed by the result of the Free Soil convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] These abolitionists had objected to Hale in spite of his spirited opposition to the gag rule; they were hardly inclined to support Van Buren, who had endorsed the gag rule as president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The platform adopted by the National Liberty Party at Buffalo completed the separation of the Liberty Leaguers from the majority faction of the Liberty Party who would go on to support Van Buren and the free soil movement in the general election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The delegates approved a preamble and thirteen resolutions rejecting the result of the "spurious" 1847 Liberty Party convention and declaring the National Liberty Party a "permanent" organization committed to universal application of the doctrine of equal rights.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] In pointed contrast to the more moderate position staked out by the Free Soilers, they declared all proslavery laws and constitutions to be null and void and asserted the power and obligation of the United States Congress to abolish slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] They endorsed the free-produce movement and the recent escape attempt by 77 enslaved people in Washington, D.C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] Despite the optimism of the Free Soilers, Van Buren carried no electoral votes, finishing a distant third behind Cass and Taylor.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] His 10.13% of the popular vote, however, represents a dramatic improvement on Birney's 1844 result, owing largely to his popularity with antislavery Democrats.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The National Liberty Party attracted sparse support; Smith received votes in only four states, including his native New York, where he polled 2,454 votes (0.56%).
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-free-soil-liberty-national-conventions] The Free Soil platform of 1848 provided the policy basis for the antislavery coalition that would come to power in the election of 1860 as the Republican Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 7, 1848 in the aftermath of the Mexican–American War.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] General Zachary Taylor of the Whig Party defeated Senator Lewis Cass of the Democratic Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Despite his unclear political alignment and Whig opposition to the Mexican–American War in which Taylor had led American forces to victory, the 1848 Whig National Convention nominated the popular general over party stalwarts Henry Clay and Daniel Webster.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] For vice president, the Whigs nominated Millard Fillmore from New York, known for moderate views on slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Polk, a Democrat, refused to seek re-election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The 1848 Democratic National Convention nominated Senator Lewis Cass of Michigan after former President Martin Van Buren withdrew his bid for a third and nonconsecutive nomination over a platform dispute.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren, from New York, instead broke from the Democratic Party to win the nomination of the Free Soil Party, which opposed the extension of slavery into the territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats had a record of prosperity and had acquired vast lands including Texas, the Mexican Cession, and the southern portion of the Oregon Country.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] They appeared certain to win unless the Whigs masked their prior opposition to the successful war by nominating Taylor.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor won a popular plurality and an electoral majority, while Van Buren won 10.1% of the popular vote, a strong showing for a third party candidate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor was the second Whig to win a Presidential election, following fellow general William Henry Harrison's victory in 1840.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Like Harrison, Taylor died in office, and was succeeded by Fillmore.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Party held its national convention in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, with delegates from every state except for Texas although the Texas Whigs had selected to make the Louisiana delegates their proxies.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Henry Clay, Winfield Scott, Zachary Taylor, and Daniel Webster sought the presidential nomination and Taylor led on every ballot before winning on the fourth ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] After Webster turned down the vice presidential candidacy, Millard Fillmore received the party's vice-presidential nomination on the second ballot after defeating Abbott Lawrence, a Massachusetts politician whose mild opposition to slavery led him to be dubbed a "Cotton Whig".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] An attempt was made to make both nominations unanimous, but it was unsuccessful due to Taylor's support for the Whig Party being seen as dubious.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party held its national convention in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] There was a credentials dispute over the New York delegation between the Barnburners and Hunkers factions with the Barnburners being anti-slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The delegates voted 126 to 125 to seat both delegations and share their control of New York's votes, but the Barnburners left the convention in disagreement with the compromise while the Hunkers refused to vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The withdrawal of the Barnburners effectively removed former President Martin Van Buren, who had already become unenthusiastic about trying to win the party's nomination after the convention had voted to endorse a platform supporting popular sovereignty, from contention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of Van Buren's withdrawal, U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Senator Lewis Cass and Secretary of State James Buchanan were seen as the only serious contenders for the presidential nomination, with a draft effort also focusing on Supreme Court associate justice Levi Woodbury.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] William Orlando Butler won the vice-presidential nomination on the second ballot against John A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Members of the Whig Party who opposed slavery, New York Barnburners, and members of the Liberty Party met in August 1848 in Buffalo, New York, to found a new political party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Barnburners made a call for the formation of an anti-slavery party at their conclave in June, and by the People's Convention of Friends of Free Territory, which was organized by Salmon P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was attended by 165 delegates from eight states to form the Free Soil Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren won the party's presidential nomination against John P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hale on the first ballot with 244 votes against Hale's 181 votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hale had been nominated by the Liberty Party in October 1847, but withdrew from the election after the Free Soil Party gave its presidential nomination to Van Buren.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Charles Francis Adams Sr. won the party's vice-presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Van Buren knew that the Free Soilers had not the slightest chance of winning, rather that his candidacy would split the Democratic vote and throw the election to the Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Bitter and aging, Van Buren did not care despite the fact that his life had been built upon the rock of party solidarity and party regularity.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] He loathed Lewis Cass and the principle of popular sovereignty with equal intensity.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Despite their significant showing in the prior presidential election, certain events would conspire to remove the Liberty Party from political significance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Initially, the party's presidential nomination was to be decided in the fall of 1847 at a Convention in Buffalo, New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hale was nominated for president over Gerrit Smith, brother-in-law to the party's previous presidential nominee James G.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Leicester King, a former judge and state senator in Ohio, was nominated for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Democrats and Whigs, disappointed with their respective nominees, would form a new movement in conjunction with members of the Liberty Party such as John Hale and Salmon Chase to form the Free Soil Party that summer.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] At this point, both Hale and King withdrew in favor of a Free Soil ticket led by former President Martin Van Buren, and the great majority of members of the Liberty Party followed them into the new political party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] A small faction refused to support Van Buren for the presidency, however.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] They held another convention in June 1848 as the *"National Liberty Party."* Gerrit Smith was nominated for president with Charles C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Foote, a Presbyterian minister from Michigan, as his vice presidential running mate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Native American Party, a precursor to the Know Nothings, which had split from the Whig Party in 1845, met in September 1847 in Philadelphia, where they nominated Zachary Taylor for president and Henry A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Dearborn of Massachusetts for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] However, when the Whig Party nominated Taylor for the presidency with Millard Fillmore as his running mate the following year, this rendered his previous nomination moot and the Native American Party failed to make an alternate nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Industrial Congress held in Philadelphia on June 13, 1848, nominating Gerrit Smith (nominee of the National Liberty Party) for president, and William S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This meeting, inspired by the National Reform Association, was primarily focused on workers rights.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] It established a platform that included planks on land limitation, the reduction of public official's salaries, abolition of the standing army, tariff reduction, and a reduced work week.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was fought without much enthusiasm, and practically without an issue.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Neither of the two great parties made an effort to rally the people to the defense of any important principle.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Whig campaigners, who included future presidents Abraham Lincoln and Rutherford B.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Hayes, talked up Taylor's "antiparty" opposition to the Jacksonian commitment to the spoils system and yellow-dog partisanship.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In the South, they stressed that he was a Louisiana slaveholder, while in the North they highlighted his Whiggish willingness to defer to Congress on major issues (which he subsequently did not do).
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats repeated, as they had for many years, their opposition to a national bank, high tariffs, and federal subsidies for local improvements.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soilers branded both major parties lackeys of the Slave Power, arguing that the rich planters controlled the agenda of both parties, leaving the ordinary white man out of the picture.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] They had to work around Van Buren's well-known reputation for compromising with slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs had the advantage of highlighting Taylor's military glories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] With Taylor remaining vague on the issues, the campaign was dominated by personalities and personal attacks, with the Democrats calling Taylor vulgar, uneducated, cruel and greedy, and the Whigs attacking Cass for graft and dishonesty.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The division of the Democrats over slavery allowed Taylor to dominate the Northeast.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soilers were on the ballots in only 17 of the 29 states with the popular vote, making it mathematically possible for Van Buren to win the presidency, but he had no real chance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Still, the party campaigned vigorously, particularly in the traditional Democratic strongholds in the northeast.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] While some Free Soilers were hopeful of taking enough states to throw the election into the House of Representatives, Van Buren himself knew this was a long shot and that the best that his party could do was lay the groundwork for a hopefully improved showing in 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first time in the Second Party System in which the victorious party failed to gain at least a plurality of the counties as well as of the popular vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last election in which Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Georgia, Louisiana, Maryland, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Rhode Island voted for the Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] It was also the last time that Georgia voted against the Democrats until 1964, the last time Delaware and Louisiana did so until 1872, and the last time Florida and North Carolina did so until 1868.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Discounting Republican Abraham Lincoln's 1864 re-election on the National Union ticket, Taylor is the most recent individual who was not a member of either the Democratic Party or the Republican Party to win a presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The contest was the first presidential election that took place on the same day in every state, and it was the first time that Election Day was statutorily a Tuesday.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] It is also the first election in which the two candidates that received electoral votes carried the same number of states and the only time that it happened between Democrat and Whig candidates.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] This would only happen again twice, in 1880 and 2020.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] 28.6% of the voting age population and 72.8% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] With Taylor as their candidate, the Whigs won their second and last victory in a presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor won the electoral college by capturing 163 of the 290 electoral votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor out-polled Cass in the popular vote by 138,000 votes, winning 47% of the popular vote, and was elected president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] A study of the county returns reveals that Free Soil strength drawn at the expense of the major parties differed by region.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In the East North Central States, it appears at least the majority of the Free Soil strength was drawn from the Whig Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Conversely, in the Middle Atlantic region, Free Soil bases of strength lay in the areas which had hitherto been Democratic, particularly in New York and northern Pennsylvania.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Democrats nomination of Van Buren made the victory of Taylor nearly certain in New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] On election day, enough Democratic votes were drawn away by Van Buren to give the Whig ticket all but two Democratic counties, thus enabling it to carry hitherto impregnable parts of upper New York state.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats, confronted with an irreparable schism in New York, lost the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In New England, the Democratic vote declined by 33,000 from its 1844 level, while the Whig vote likewise declined by 15,000 votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The third-party vote tripled, and the total vote remained nearly stationary: a partial indication, perhaps, of the derivation of the Free Soil strength in this section.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] For the first time since the existence of the Whig Party, the Whigs failed to gain an absolute majority of the vote in Massachusetts and Vermont.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] In addition, the Democrats failed to retain their usual majority in Maine; thus only New Hampshire (Democratic) and Rhode Island (Whig) of the states in this section gave their respective victorious parties clear-cut majorities.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] Four counties (0.27%) in the West split evenly between Taylor and Cass.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-united-states-presidential-election] The election has sometimes been described as "a contest without an issue," as both major candidates sought to steer clear of divisive subjects.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The **1848 Whig National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention held from June 7 to 9 in Philadelphia.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] It nominated the Whig Party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1848 election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The convention selected General Zachary Taylor of Louisiana for president and former Representative Millard Fillmore of New York for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Taylor and General Winfield Scott had both emerged as contenders for the Whig presidential nomination after serving in the Mexican–American War, while two long-time party leaders, Senator Henry Clay of Kentucky and Senator Daniel Webster of Massachusetts, also commanded support in the party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] With Southern delegates united around his candidacy, Taylor took the lead on the first ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Clay finished a strong second to Taylor on the first ballot of the convention, but his support faded on subsequent ballots and Taylor took the nomination on the fourth ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] After Webster declined the vice presidential nomination, Fillmore and businessman Abbott Lawrence of Massachusetts emerged as the top choices for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Fillmore clinched the nomination on the second ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The Whig ticket went on to win the 1848 presidential election, defeating the Democratic ticket of Lewis Cass and William O.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The convention was held from June 7 to 9 in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Every state was represented except for Texas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Taylor had been courted by both the Democrats and the Whigs, but ultimately declared himself a Whig.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The platform adopted largely consisted of praise for Taylor, with less attention paid to specific policies.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The venue for the convention was the Chinese Museum Building.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] The building since was destroyed by fire in 1854.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] There were 280 individuals seated as delegates to the convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] By 1847, General Zachary Taylor had emerged as a contender for the Whig nomination in the 1848 presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Despite Taylor's largely unknown political views, many Whigs believed he was the party's strongest possible candidate due to his martial accomplishments in the Mexican–American War.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Henry Clay initially told his allies that he would not run in the 1848 presidential election, but he was unwilling to support Taylor, a "mere military man.".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Although Daniel Webster and General Winfield Scott each commanded a limited base of support in the party, Taylor and Clay each saw the other as their lone serious rival for the Whig nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Taylor led on the first ballot and grew his lead on subsequent ballots.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] On the fourth ballot, he secured 171 votes and won the presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Whig Party leader Thurlow Weed hoped to secure the vice presidency for former New York governor William H.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Seward, a vocal opponent of slavery, or to have him appointed U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] New Yorkers opposed to Seward promoted Millard Fillmore, the New York State Comptroller, for vice president; under the conventions of the time, two top positions could not go to individuals from the same state.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Former congressman Solomon Foot of Vermont went to the convention as a supporter of Abbott Lawrence for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] As a key Taylor supporter, Lawrence expected to be nominated.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Northern anti-slavery delegates perceived Lawrence as more accepting of slavery than Fillmore.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Recognizing that the Whigs would likely collapse if Lawrence was nominated and the northern anti-slavery delegates left the party, or if southern delegates left following a Seward nomination, Foot agreed to shift his support to Fillmore.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Lawrence's support eroded as other northern delegates followed Foot's lead, and on the first ballot, Fillmore had 115 votes and Lawrence 109.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] (Seward was subsequently elected to the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Webster was offered the vice presidential spot on the ticket, but declined.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1848-whig-national-convention] Former New York Representative Millard Fillmore was chosen as the vice presidential candidate on the second ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States on November 2, 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic nominee Franklin Pierce defeated Whig nominee General Winfield Scott.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent Whig President Millard Fillmore had succeeded to the presidency in 1850 upon the death of President Zachary Taylor.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Fillmore endorsed the Compromise of 1850 and enforced the Fugitive Slave Law.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] This earned Fillmore Southern voter support and Northern voter opposition.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] On the 53rd ballot of the sectionally divided 1852 Whig National Convention, Scott defeated Fillmore for the nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Democrats divided among four major candidates at the 1852 Democratic National Convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] On the 49th ballot, dark horse candidate Franklin Pierce won nomination by consensus compromise.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Party, a third party opposed to the extension of slavery in the United States and into the territories, nominated New Hampshire Senator John P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] With few policy differences between the two major candidates, the election became a personality contest.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Though Scott had commanded in the Mexican–American War, Pierce also served.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Scott strained Whig Party unity as his anti-slavery reputation gravely damaged his campaign in the South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Southern Whigs and a separate group of Southern Democrats each nominated insurgent tickets, but both efforts failed to attract support.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] King won a comfortable popular majority, carrying 27 of the 31 states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pierce won the highest share of the electoral vote since James Monroe's uncontested 1820 re-election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Party regressed to less than five percent of the national popular vote, down from more than ten percent in 1848, while overwhelming defeat and disagreement about slavery soon drove the Whig Party to disintegrate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-slavery Whigs and Free Soilers would ultimately coalesce into the new Republican Party, which would quickly become a formidable movement in the free states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Not until 1876 would Democrats again win a majority of the popular vote for president, and not until 1932 would they win a majority in both the popular vote and the electoral college.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic Party held its national convention in Baltimore, Maryland, in June 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Hallett, the chair of the Democratic National Committee, limited the sizes of the delegations to their electoral votes and a vote to maintain the two-thirds requirement for the presidential and vice-presidential nomination was passed by a vote of 269 to 13.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Douglas were the main candidates for the nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] All of the candidates led the ballot for the presidential nomination at one point, but all of them failed to meet the two-thirds requirement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Franklin Pierce was put up for the nomination by the Virginia delegation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pierce won the nomination when the delegates switched their support to him after he had received the unanimous support of the delegates from New England.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] He won on the second day of balloting after forty-nine ballots.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The delegation from Maine proposed that the vice-presidential nomination should be given to somebody from the Southern United States with William R.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] King led on the first ballot before winning on the second ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Whig Party held its national convention in Baltimore, Maryland, in June 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The call for the convention had been made by Whig members of the United States Congress and thirty-one states were represented.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A vote to have each state's vote be based on its electoral college strength was passed by a vote of 149 to 144, but it was rescinded due to disagreements from the Southern states and smaller Northern states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party had been divided by the Compromise of 1850 and was divided over the presidential nomination between incumbent president Millard Fillmore, who received support from the South, and Winfield Scott, who received his support from the North.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Seward, who had been the main opponent of the compromise in the United States Senate and advised President Zachary Taylor against it, supported Scott.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Fillmore offered to give his delegates to Daniel Webster if he received the support of forty-one delegates on his own, but Webster was unsuccessful.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Scott won the nomination on the 53rd ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] William Alexander Graham won the vice-presidential nomination without a formal vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Nine southern Whig members of Congress, including Alexander H.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Stephens and Robert Toombs, refused to support Scott.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Free Soil Party was still the strongest third party in 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] However, following the Compromise of 1850, most of the "Barnburners" who supported it in 1848 had returned to the Democratic Party while most of the Conscience Whigs rejoined the Whig Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The second Free Soil National Convention assembled in the Masonic Hall in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Hale was nominated for president with 192 delegate votes (sixteen votes were cast for a smattering of candidates).
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Julian of Indiana was nominated for vice president over Samuel Lewis of Ohio and Joshua R.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A movement among disaffected Whigs to nominate Daniel Webster began in earnest following the Whig National Convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] As Webster made his way from Washington to his farm in Franklin, New Hampshire, many Whigs expressed their continued loyalty to him; some spoke of forming a new "Union" party with Webster as its presidential candidate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster received letters pressuring him to endorse the new party movement, hoping he'd allow his name to be used by an opposition convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In Boston, the Webster movement was led by those who had opposed Scott's nomination, most notably George Ticknor Curtis, who had served controversially as a federal fugitive slave commissioner.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] These men had grown tired of military chieftains at the top of the Whig ticket and argued that the party had fallen under the control of dangerous foes of the Compromise.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They lacked political experience and had little to lose.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] When Webster reached Boston, the city held a huge celebration in his honor, which was "by far the most impressive and touching demonstration ever made by that people toward Mr.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Those who had stuck with Webster throughout the nomination season knew that an independent bid was hopeless.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They feared that his candidacy would damage the Whig Party and tarnish his legacy as the great "Defender of the Constitution." Although opposed to his nomination, Webster met Curtis in Marshfield and told him that he could not prevent anyone from voting for him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Privately, he was convinced that the Whig Party was disintegrating and that endorsing its ticket would be both futile and demeaning.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In fact, he held a favorable view of Pierce and advised his assistant, Charles Lanman, along with Peter Harvey, to vote for him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster would never publicly comment on the nomination movement, which at this point had spread to New York and would shortly receive the endorsement of one faction of the Georgia Constitutional Union Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, a group of pro-Webster Whigs nominated electors pledged to Webster and Graham, the Whig nominee for vice president, prompting Graham to disavow the Webster movement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, encouraged by the actions of the Georgia Union Whigs, Curtis and his followers held a convention at Faneuil Hall in Boston on September 15 and endorsed the nominations made by the Georgia Unionist convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] However, in early September, Webster's health seriously declined.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] During his final days, his friends attempted to persuade him to denounce the independent movement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They abandoned their efforts after Abbot, who had initially favored a formal statement of party loyalty, concluded that it was unfair for them to pressure a dying man who had lost all interest in politics.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Considering it useless to trouble him further, Curtis, on October 21, ordered the Webster Executive Committee in Boston to suspend activities.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster died nine days before the election of a cerebral hemorrhage on October 24, 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitutional Union Party was a political party organized in several slave states to support the Compromise of 1850.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was one of two major parties in the state of Georgia in the early 1850s, alongside the Southern Rights Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party formed as a merger of the local Democratic and Whig unionists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] While former Whigs in the party were given important positions, such as senate seats, the party's executive committee was made up of mostly Democrats.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Following the acquiescence of the Southern Rights leaders to the Compromise after 1851, the need for a dedicated Union party diminished.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] With a supermajority in the state legislature, the Union Party began its program of division of the political spoils, which eventually led to a split between the Democratic and Whig factions.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Party leaders adopted a wait-and-see attitude as the presidential election approached.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In April, Union Democrats held a state convention that nominated delegates to attend the Democratic National Convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Union Whigs held their own convention later that summer and appointed a delegation led by William C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Dawson to attend the Whig National Convention, instructing them to support the nomination of Millard Fillmore.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] These separate conventions laid the groundwork for the party's eventual collapse, providing Union Democrats with an excuse to return to the Democratic fold.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Although the Union Democrats supported Pierce as the national Democratic nominee, they refused to support the state Pierce ticket nominated by the Southern Rights Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, they ran their own ticket with the tacit consent of Governor Howell Cobb.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] At the subsequent Constitutional Union state convention on July 15, the Union Democrats were able to nominate an electoral ticket pledged to Pierce, causing Union Whigs to walk out of the convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Fearing that Scott would repudiate the Compromise, they nominated Webster in a convention at Macon with Charles J.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Jenkins as the candidate for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pro-Scott Whigs held a concurrent convention in Macon, but a fusion of the two groups failed to occur.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Following these conventions, the Democratic majority on the Constitutional Union Party's executive committee declared the party dissolved and withdrew the independent Pierce ticket.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Around the mid-1830s, nativists were present in New York politics, under the aegis of the American Republican Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The American Republican party was formed in 1843 in major opposition to Catholicism and Catholic immigrants.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In 1845, the party changed its name to the Native American Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Their opponents nicknamed them the "Know Nothings".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party liked the name, and it became the official nickname of the party until it collapsed in 1860.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In 1852, the original presidential nominee planned by the Native American Party was Daniel Webster, the presidential nominee of the Union Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They nominated Webster without his permission, with George C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Washington (grandnephew of George Washington) as his vice presidential running mate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Webster died of natural causes nine days before the election, and the Know-Nothings quickly replaced Webster by nominating Jacob Broom for president and replaced Washington with Reynell Coates for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Southern Rights Party was a political party organized in several slave states to oppose the Compromise of 1850, viewing it as inadequate protection for the South, and advocate for secession from the Union, though it later abandoned serious plans for secession.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was one of two major parties in the states of Alabama, Georgia, and Mississippi in the early 1850s, alongside the Union Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party was made up of mostly Democrats and State Rights Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] By 1851, most Southern Rights Democrats had acquiesced to the compromise, believing further opposition to it was hopeless.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was unclear in early 1852 if the remnants of the party would contest the presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] When the Southern Rights Convention of Alabama in Montgomery was held in early March, only six counties were represented.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The convention voted to keep the party alive throughout the southern states to oppose both the Democrats and Whigs, or cooperate with either based on the extent to which their doctrines aligned with the principles of the Southern Rights men.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the party was too disorganized to nominate its own candidate and have an effect on the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The South Carolinian *Southern Standard* argued that the Southern Rights parties should coordinate and attempt to influence the Democratic nomination, though not by joining the Democratic convention, as that might obligate them to support an unfavorable candidate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the paper proposed holding a parallel convention at the same time and place, so they could be "prepared to act as circumstances might require".
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] After the Democratic National Convention, the party was not sure that it wanted to support Franklin Pierce and William R.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Another Southern Rights Convention was held in Montgomery from July 13–15 and debated at length whether to keep up a separate organization and whether they wanted to nominate Pierce.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The convention was unable to arrive at a decision, deciding to appoint a committee to review the positions of Scott/Graham and Pierce/King, with the option of calling a "national" convention if the two major-party tickets appeared deficient.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The committee took its time reviewing the positions of Pierce and Scott, finally deciding on August 25 to call a convention for a Southern Rights Party ticket.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Pierce had failed to answer their inquiry and on August 27 it was reported that Scort replied to the letter of the Alabama Southern Rights Central Committee, but declined giving specitic answers to their interrogatories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The convention assembled in Montgomery, Alabama, with 62 delegates present, a committee to recommend a ticket being appointed while the delegates listened to speeches in the interim.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The committee eventually recommended former senator George Troup of Georgia for president, and former governor John Quitman of Mississippi for vice president; they were unanimously nominated.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The two nominees accepted their nominations soon after the convention, which was held rather late in the season.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Troup stated in a letter, dated September 27 and printed in the New York Times on October 16, that he had planned to vote for Pierce/King and had always wholeheartedly supported William R.D.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] He indicated in the letter that he preferred to decline the honor, as he was rather ill at the time and feared that he would die before the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The state party's executive committee edited the letter to excise those portions which indicated that Troup preferred to decline, a fact which was revealed after the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Seeking to gain favor of the successful national party, whom would most likely be the Democrats, the Resistance Party, as the Georgian branch was known, changed its name to the Southern Rights Party and held a convention on March 31, 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] At this convention, it nominated delegates to the national Democratic convention and an electoral ticket headed by Herschel V.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] These men were instructed to show no preference for any particular candidate, although a large majority of the convention that nominated them supported Buchanan as their first choice.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] In April, the Democrats in the Constitutional Union Party had held a convention where they nominated delegates to the national Democratic convention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Following the dissolution of the Constitutional Union Party, Georgia Democrats and the Southern Rights Party met in a joint convention and attempted to consolidate support for Pierce in a combined Southern Rights-Democratic ticket.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Liberty Party had ceased to become a significant political force after most of its members joined the Free Soil Party in 1848.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Nonetheless, some of those who rejected the fusion strategy held a Liberty Party National Convention in Buffalo, New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] There were few delegates present, so a ticket was recommended and a later convention called.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Convention recommended Gerrit Smith of New York for president and Charles Durkee of Wisconsin for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A second convention was held in Syracuse, New York, in early September 1852, but it too failed to draw enough delegates to select nominees.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Yet a third convention gathered in Syracuse later that month and nominated William Goodell of New York for president and S.M.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] A slate of electors nominated by the Liberty Party received 72 votes in New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Whigs' platform was almost indistinguishable from that of the Democrats, reducing the campaign to a contest between the personalities of the two candidates.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The lack of clearcut issues between the two parties helped drive voter turnout down to its lowest level since 1836.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The decline was further exacerbated by Scott's antislavery reputation, which decimated the Southern Whig vote at the same time as the pro-slavery Whig platform undermined the Northern Whig vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] After the Compromise of 1850 was passed, many of the southern Whig Party members broke with the party's key figure, Henry Clay.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Finally, Scott's status as a war hero was somewhat offset by the fact that Pierce was himself a Mexican–American War brigadier general.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats adopted the slogan: *The Whigs we Polked in forty-four, We'll Pierce in fifty-two*, playing on the names of Pierce and former president James K.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Just nine days before the election, Webster died, causing many Union state parties to remove their slates of electors.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Union ticket appeared on the ballot in Georgia and Massachusetts, however.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] 27.3% of the voting age population and 69.5% of eligible voters participated in the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The fact that Daniel Webster received a substantial share of the vote in Georgia and Massachusetts, even though he was dead, shows how disenchanted voters were with the two main candidates.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] As a result of the devastating defeat and the growing tensions within the party between pro-slavery Southerners and anti-slavery Northerners, the Whig Party quickly fell apart after the 1852 election and ceased to exist.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Some Southern Whigs would join the Democratic Party, and many Northern Whigs would help to form the new Republican Party in 1854.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Some Whigs in both sections would support the so-called "Know-Nothing" party in the 1856 presidential election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Similarly, the Free Soil Party rapidly fell away into obscurity after the election, and the remaining members mostly opted to join the former Northern Whigs in forming the Republican Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Southern Rights Party effectively collapsed following the election, attaining only five percent of the vote in Alabama, and a few hundred in its nominee's home state of Georgia.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It would elect a number of Congressmen in 1853, but they would rejoin the Democratic Party upon taking their seats in Congress.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky and Tennessee were the only slave states that Scott won.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] None of the future Confederate states elected governors in the 1852 and 1853 gubernatorial elections, and the Whigs only won 14 of the South's 65 seats in the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The party held no state legislatures in the South except in Tennessee.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The Democrats, who carried all but two northern states, would see a decline in the north following the 1854 elections due to controversy around the Kansas–Nebraska Act.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] They lost control of all free state legislatures except for two, and their seats in the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] House from the north fell from 93 to 23.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] The four elections from 1840 to 1852 saw the incumbent party defeated each time; the only other such streak was from 1884 to 1896.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] It was, however, the last election in which the Democrats' chief opponent won Kentucky until 1896, and the last until 1928 in which the Democrats' opponent obtained an absolute majority in Kentucky.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1852-united-states-presidential-election] *United States Presidential Elections, 1788–1860* pp 115-134 with differences with Walter Dean Burnham, *Presidential ballots, 1836–1892* (Johns Hopkins University Press, 1955) pp 247–57 noted.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The **1856 Democratic National Convention** was a presidential nominating convention that met from June 2 to June 6 in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] It was held to nominate the Democratic Party's candidates for president and vice president in the 1856 election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The convention selected former Secretary of State James Buchanan of Pennsylvania for president and former Representative John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Breckinridge of Kentucky for vice president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Incumbent Democratic President Franklin Pierce's standing with the public had been badly damaged by "Bleeding Kansas," the civil strife in Kansas Territory over slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Many dissatisfied Democrats lined up behind Buchanan, who had served as Pierce's ambassador to Britain and thus had avoided the controversy over Bleeding Kansas, while a smaller group of Democrats supported Senator Stephen A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Buchanan led on the first ballot and slowly grew his support on subsequent ballots, leading Pierce to instruct his delegates to back Douglas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Douglas agreed to withdraw his name after receiving assurances that Buchanan would not seek re-election in 1860, allowing Buchanan to clinch the nomination on the seventeenth ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Pierce became the first and only elected president who was an active candidate for reelection to be denied his party's nomination for a second term.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Eleven candidates received votes on the first vice presidential ballot, with Congressman John A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Quitman winning a plurality of the vote.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The delegates lined up unanimously behind Breckinridge on the second ballot, giving him the vice presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic ticket went on to win the 1856 election, defeating the Republican ticket of John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Dayton and the American Party ticket of Millard Fillmore and Andrew J.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The Democratic Party was wounded from its major losses in the 1854–1855 midterm elections.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The party faced continued north–south sectional division over slavery-related issues, especially the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854 and subsequent violence known as "Bleeding Kansas" from the civil strife in the Kansas Territory during its campaign for statehood.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Two notable Democratic politicians, President Pierce and Senator Stephen Douglas of Illinois, were seen as being at the center of the controversies, which led many party members to look elsewhere for a new compromise candidate for president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] James Buchanan had been a candidate for president at the 1852 Democratic National Convention, and after the 1852 election he agreed to serve as Pierce's ambassador to Britain.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Buchanan's service abroad conveniently placed him outside of the country while the debate over the Kansas–Nebraska Act roiled the nation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Powerful Senators like John Slidell, Jesse Bright, and James A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Bayard lined up behind Buchanan, presenting him as an experienced leader who could appeal to the North and South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] While Buchanan did not overtly seek the presidency, he also took no action to discourage his supporters.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Called to order at noon on Monday, June 2, by the National Committee chair Robert Milligan McLane, Samuel Medary was made the temporary president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The first day, the convention appointed committees on credentials, organization, and resolutions.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] On the second day the organization committee (John L.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Dawson, chair) report was adopted and John Elliot Ward of Georgia was made the convention's president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Bayard Jr., chair) settled a dispute over the Missouri delegation, but needed more time for the thorny problem of competing delegations from New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] June 4 saw the adoption of a platform (former National Committee chair Benjamin F.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Hallett headed the committee on resolutions); the domestic portions were supported unanimously, the foreign policy planks by large margins.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] A separately reported plank on a railroad to the Pacific coast failed by a vote of 120 to 154.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] On June 5, the New York problem was finally settled by seating half of each of the competing delegations.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Nominations for President were then made.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] On the first ballot, Pierce received 122 votes, many of them from the South, to Buchanan's 135, with Douglas and Lewis Cass receiving the remaining votes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The next four ballots produced largely the same result, but Pierce's support began to gradually decline starting on the sixth ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Buchanan's support steadily increased over the course of the vote, but the biggest momentum was with Douglas, who started the day with the support of only a few midwestern delegations and had nearly doubled his delegate count by the time balloting adjourned for the day.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] By the end of the day fourteen ballots had been completed; while none of the three main candidates were able to get two-thirds of the vote, it was by now obvious that Pierce would not be nominated for a second term.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Douglas, only 43 years of age, believed that he could be nominated in 1860 if he let the older Buchanan win this time, and received assurances from Buchanan's managers that this would be the case.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] After two more deadlocked ballots, Douglas's managers withdrew his name, leaving Buchanan as the clear winner.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] To soften the blow to Pierce, the convention issued a resolution of "unqualified approbation" in praise of his administration.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] This loss marked the first (and until 2024, only) time in U.S. history that an elected president who was an active candidate for reelection was not nominated for a second term.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Eleven candidates were nominated for the vice presidency, but a number of them attempted to withdraw themselves from consideration, among them the eventual nominee, John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Breckinridge supported fellow Kentuckian Linn Boyd for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] On the first ballot, Representative John A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Quitman of Mississippi was the front-runner, but his extreme pro-slavery views meant he no real prospect of gaining the required two-thirds majority.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Following a draft effort led by the delegation from Vermont, Breckinridge was nominated unanimously on the second ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] The Buchanan-Breckinridge ticket went on to win the 1856 presidential election, defeating John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/1856-democratic-national-convention] Dayton from the new Republican Party, and a strong third party showing from the American Party of the "Know Nothings" represented by former President Millard Fillmore and Andrew J.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:abraham-lincoln/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
